Subject: install.sh: reset --hard fallback when the release branch diverged

Re-running the install one-liner over an existing install takes install.sh's
"Existing installation found, updating..." path, which runs
`git pull --ff-only origin "$BRANCH"` under `set -e`. If origin/release was
rebuilt with rewritten history (the pre-fix orphan force-push, or any future
non-fast-forwardable update), `--ff-only` fails and `set -e` aborts the whole
installer with `fatal: refusing to merge unrelated histories` — the installer-
driven update is dead. The CLI `nadia update` already recovers from this by
falling back to `git reset --hard origin/<branch>` (hermes_cli/main.py); the
installer had no equivalent. Add the same fallback. Local changes are already
auto-stashed immediately above, so the reset is safe. Belt-and-suspenders with
the release-branch linearisation in tools/release_branch_push.py, and the only
recovery for customers still on a pre-linearisation orphan checkout. IU-AC-9.

--- a/scripts/install.sh
+++ b/scripts/install.sh
@@ -918,7 +918,11 @@ clone_repo() {
 
             git fetch origin
             git checkout "$BRANCH"
-            git pull --ff-only origin "$BRANCH"
+            # Fast-forward when possible; if the release branch was force-pushed
+            # with rewritten history, fall back to a hard reset to match the
+            # remote exactly (mirrors `hermes update`'s recovery path). Local
+            # changes are already stashed above, so the reset is safe.
+            git pull --ff-only origin "$BRANCH" || git reset --hard "origin/$BRANCH"
 
             if [ -n "$autostash_ref" ]; then
                 local restore_now="yes"
